title: For Sale:  Ishapore 2A1 7.62 NATO
postcontent: Good condition Ishapore 2A1 rifle.  Very Good condition bore, no pitting and very clean.  Loves M80 Ball and is really easy to load with 10 round M1A 308 reload kit clips.  Comes with a British 1907 pattern 1915 made sword bayonet, unaltered original length blade and comes with the scabbard, lacking a frog to attach to the belt.  The Ishapore 2A1 was made as a stop-gap rifle to replace the outdated .303 British Lee Enfield rifle, into the more modern 7.62x51NATO round before they could get any self loading rifles made.  This gun is NOT a conversion from .303 to 7.62NATO, it was designed from the ground up to fire this round and used more modern steel than the old Lee Enfield rifles.  The rifle is styled after the old No1Mk3 Short Magazine Lee Enfield rifle, and operates just like a Lee Enfield does but it fires the more available 7.62NATO round.  I have not had the headspace checked for .308 Winchester, but thicker brassed 7.62NATO spec ammo runs just fine and that is what it is intended to shoot.  I have 60 rounds of ZQI ammunition for anyone that can come and pick it up locally, I'm not familiar with the process to ship live ammunition.  I'm willing to FFL this rifle to a buyer.  The black paint on the metal that came from the factory is slightly worn.  The rifles were painted instead of blued from the factory in India.

title: For Sale:  Model 1855 Rifle Musket
postcontent: The widespread complaints from US Army units about the Maynard Tape Priming System led the Army to convene an Ordnance Board in May 1860 under Major Alfred Mordecai to study the problem. After examining the problem with the Model 1855 and reviewing numerous reports, the Board issued a report with several recommendations. The Board first noted that virtually all of the reports from company commanders whose soldiers were issued the Model 1855, and from the Army's Inspectors General, agreed that the Maynard Tape Priming System was unreliable for "general service; and it appears that no commanding officers are willing to trust to the use of them separately from the percussion cap..." Major Mordecai and the Ordnance Board then take a not-so-subtle swipe at the Ordnance Department's original decision to adopt the Model 1855 Rifle Musket when he writes that the reports from the field were "confirming the doubts expressed by the Ordnance Board with regard to the adoption of the system, when this subject was first presented to them in 1854." The Model 1855 Rifle Musket, which was already in the field but which was just made obsolete by the Ordnance Department's decision to completely scrap its percussion system, was only made at the United States' two national armories, Springfield Armory and Harpers Ferry Armory. With war imminent, the radical change to the principal shoulder arm of the United States Army would require both national armories to rapidly re-tool and equip to begin producing the new model rifle as quickly as possible. This plan received a major blow when, just two months after the new changes were authorized, on April 18, 1861, Virginia Militia troops captured Harpers Ferry Armory, leaving Springfield Armory as the sole national armory for the war that was just beginning. And the Union Army would not even have the full benefit of the more than 60,000 Model 1855 Rifle Muskets, with the now obsolete Maynard Tape Primer System because an inventory dated October 10, 1860, listed only 22,649 of these rifles in US Government arsenals. Of these, 7,431 of the rifles were in US armories located in what would become the Confederacy and these rifles would initially serve the Confederate, not the Union Army.modified barrel bands, a modified hammer, deletion of the retaining swell in the ramrod, addition of a ramrod retaining spring, and enlarged stock wrist. Additionally, the finish to the furniture was changed. The lock and hammer were color case hardened and, initially, the barrel bands were left in the white or national armory bright. Later in 1863, Springfield Type I production barrel bands were blued. This change in finish of barrel bands helps date Model 1863 Rifles manufactured in 1863 since those with armory bright barrel bands were probably produced from April to August or September 1863. These changes, as incorporated in the new rifle, are referred to as the Model 1863 Rifle, Type I. These changes were again mirrored in small ways by some of the contractors in late 1863 and 1864. The Trigger Plate and Trigger Guard Bow are original and are in fine condition. There is no pitting or corrosion on the trigger plate and it is assuming a pewter patina with areas of plum towards the rear portion. The Trigger Guard Bow has a few nicks on the bottom portion and it also is assuming a mixed pewter and plum patina. The original filing marks on the bottom of the guard bow can still be seen. The rear sling swivel is in fine condition and exhibits a mixed pewter and plum patina with no pitting noted. It is still secured to the guard bow with the flush screw and is center punched on the left side to secure the swivel to the bow. The swivel still moves freely. The Trigger is in fine condition and exhibits a mixed plum and pewter patina on the lower, exposed surface with no pitting noted. The top portion of the trigger plate is in its fine, original condition with all of the original tool markings present and there is no discoloration except for a few small areas at either end. Both guard bow screws are present. The top of the trigger and the trigger pin are present and exhibit their original “in the white” finish. The front plate screw retains the majority of its original blue finish and the slot is only slightly marred. The rear plate screw exhibits the majority of its original blue finish on the body with the head exhibiting a mixed blue and plum patina. The rear screw slot is unmarred.No ffl, Paypal or Postal money order.
